{"/service/ndnp/wvu/batch_wvu_day_ver01/data/sn86092084/00517010881/1937120901/0801.xml":{"full_text":"Frankly .Speaking\nBT F. G. s.\nBUSINESS RECESSION Is the\nphrase that is being passed round\nlike a football these days; and there\nis nothing that can add more to build\ning up a business recess than the con\nstant chirping on that phrase. There\nIs a very fine axiom in sports to the\neffect that the best defense is a good\noffense. Some of the most pessimistic\nof the shouters of bad news about the\nbusiness recession might sharpen\ntheir appetites and get rid of that\nnervous indigestion by following the\naxiom mentioned.\n-A\nI! WITH CHRISTMAS only a couple\nof weeks off, holidav shoppers are\n\u2022jt bound to appear, and they will cer\ntainly prefer to spend their money\nwith the man who says, \u201cI have a\ngood Stock of goods here and I intend\nto do the best I can with it,\u201d in pre\nference to the salesman who greets\nhis customer with a \"Woe is me!\"\ncountenance and a tale about the fact\nthat we are all doomed.\nLOOK AT the men and the busl\nbem firms who have become birr.\nThey ffot there because they fought\nhard while things went smooth and\nthen they fought harder when ob\nstacles got in their paths. Anybody\ncan coast downhill, but the winner is\nthe man who can take the uphill\ngrades with the ditches and fences in\nhis path.\n-x\nIN THE REALM of snort the out\nstanding event of local interest seems\nto be the amateur heawweight bout\nwhich is to bring together a couple\nof local young giants who will swap\npunches for the championship in\ntheir division in the Kiwanis Benefit\nTournament being staged in the eve\nnings at the Memorial building. These\ntwo scrappers are none other than\nVerlin Adams of Wolfpack football\nfame and Goose Hensley. All rumors\ntend to the fact that each of these\nfighters will be more than anxious to\nend the melee with his opponent in a\nrestful, horizontal position. Fights\nare carded for tonight and tomorrow\nnight. Don\u2019t miss them, folks, for\nregardless of the fact that they will\nprove thrilling and good entertain\nment, there is also the fact that the\nproceeds are to be used for one of tb_e\nbest of causes: the fund for under\nprivileged children.\nW. E. DAVIS IMPROVES\nWilliam E. Davis, superintendent\nOf the Howard Colliery is home\nfrom Huntington where he was a\n'Surgical patient at St. Masys hospital.\n|je is reported as improving at his\nhome at Chattaroy.\nKIDNAPPER ON TRIAL\nArnett Booth, alleged kidnapper of\nthe late James I. Seder, is on trial for\nhis life in a Cabel county court at\nHuntington.\nIndex Of Advertisers\nAlberts\nArcade Cleaners\nAppalachian Electric Power Co.\nBAB Beauty Shoppe\nBassett\u2019s\nBayer Aspirin\nBen Burke, Inc.\nBrunswick Billiard Parlor\nClassic\nCoca-Cola Bottling Co.\nM. C. DIngess\nFirst National Bank\nGates \"Radio Sales A Service Co.\nOtis's Place\nHankins Tee Co.\nHarrison Burial Association\nHoeran Storage A Transfer Co.\nHurley Drug Co.\nT.ewls Furniture Co.\nMountaineer Dry Cleaners\nSears, \"Roebuck And Co.\nSmek\u00bb House\nSouthern Auto Stores\nSutrar Bowl\nSweet Shop\nV. S. Taylor\u2019s Esso Station\nDr. C. H. Temple the Chiropractor\nTutr River Insurance Agency\nFnlted Fuel Gas Co.\nJ. D. Westcott A Son\nWilliamson Refrigeration Co.\nWilliamson Supply Co.\nlc\u00e4ln\nO\nepubl\nB\n[VOLUME XXXIV\u2014No. 37\nWTTXIAMSON, WEST VIRGINIA, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 9, 1937\nESTABLISHED APRIL, UN\n'AS CAMERA SAW LINDBERGHS AT DINNER ABOARD SHIP\nfainMir\"nrr\n1\nCoL Charles A. Lindbergh, Mrs. Lindbergh and Capt. James E. Roberto at \u00abHnn\u00ab- aboard the Uner, Pres\nident Harding.\nBalding two years of self-imposed exile with a sur\nprise visit to his native land, Col. Charles A. Lind\nbergh, famous flyer, and his wife secretly arrived\nin New York aboard the liner President Harding,\nand rushed to the home of Mrs. Lindbergh\u2019s moth\ner, Mrs. Dwight Morrow, at Englewood, N. J. The\nLindberghs\u2019 two children, Jon, 5, and Land, six\nmonths, remained in England. This photo shows\nthe Lindberghs dining with Capt. James E. Roberts\naboard the liner en route to the United States. It\nwas taken with much difficulty by a ship news\nphotographer.\nProdigal Son Appears\nAt Methodist Church\nThe \"Prodigal Son,\u201d a Biblical play\nwritten by Capt. C. R. McDilda of\nthe Salvation Army and produced\nlast week at the high school audi\ntorium, will be given Sunday eve\nning at the First Methodist church\nin place of the regular worship.\nThe play was well received by\nthose who saw it at the auditorium,\nreflecting credit on the author and\nproducer and the excellent cast that\nassisted Capt McDilda in its rendi\ntion.\nMiss Rose G. Smith of the English\ndepartment of the high school super\nvised the production.\nThe cast of chaiacters includes\nMagistrate Robert E. Clifton as the\nFather, Eldo Faith as the Elder Broth\ner, Capt. McDilda as the Prodigal,\nA. C. Chafin as the Servant, the Rev.\nA. H. Robinson as- the Reader.\nMusiciasn include Miss Margaret\nAnn Young, soloist: Margaret Spauld\ning Cornett, pianist; Asa W. Rqese,\nJ. D. Lawrence, F. W. Burmeister\nand A. Ray Milby, members of the\nquartette, with a mixed chorus of vo\ncalists.\nj Stroke Fatal To\nE. A. Buchanan:\nA paralytic stroke suffered eight\ndays before his death resulted in the\npassing of E. A. Buchanan Friday.\nFuneral services were held Saturday.\nOn the day following his fatal\nstroke. Mr. Buchanan was to have\nstarted work as supervisor of the\ncommodity department, Department\nof Public Assistance. J\nPreviously, he had been an em-'\nploye of the State Road Commission\nand had served as supervisor of\nWPA activities in Mingo county. He\nhad also been employed in coal com\nState Man Writes Play\nPare Borcntz of Buckhannon Writes second successful film story for use of\nfederal g-ovemment's propaganda for flood control and power projects.\nWest Virginia horn Pare Borentz,\nNew York motion picture eritie. again\ntakes the spot light in the cinema\nworld with the release the Hnited\nStates Government of \"The River,\"\nthe second of two powerful films\nwritten by the former Buckhannon\nboy.\nMr. Borentz is the son of the late\nPare H. Borentz and Mrs. Borentz,\n1 of Buckhannon. He has lived In New\nYork for several years, and is recog\nnized as one of the leading cinema\ncritics of the metroplis. He has heen\na frequent contributors to national\nmagazines.\nThe film, entitled \"The River.\u201d will\nbe released by the Farm Security ad\nravishment of great sections of a con\nvey in simple terms the story of the\nwastage of national land resources\nthrough erosion.\nTn picture, poetic narration and\nmusic, the new film takes up at a\npoint where \"The Plow That Broke\nThe Plains\u201d left off in describing the\nravishment of great sections of a con\ntinent during the hasty rush to build\nfor bigness.\nIn technique the film follows the\npattern of \"The Plow,\" and It was\nshaped by the same hands. Pare\nBorentz, motion picture critic. Is\nauthor and director of both \"The\nPlow\u201d and \"The River.\u201d He wrote\nthe narratives. His American ances\ntry is pre-Revolution.\nVirgil Thompson, concert pianist\nand composer, drafted the musical\npany offices and as a traveling rep\nresentative.\nA resident of Williamson since\n1934, Mr. Buchanan is survived by\nhis widow, to whom he was mar\nried Dec. 24, 1912, in Castlewood,\nW. Va., and the following children:\nNell. Betty Lou, Mrs. Goebel Ball\nand Fred, of all of Williamson. The\nfollowing sisters and brothers also\nSurvive: Mis. Rebecca Willey, Hunt\nington; Mrs. Laura Gregory, Blue\nI field; Mrs. R. L. Hensley, Coeburn, i\nVa.; Mrs. Charles Stallard, Amon\nI ate, Va.; and C. H. Buchanan, Stone;\nand Mrs. I. J. Berns, Coeburn, Va.\nI-:\nWall Decorations\nAt Lyric Theatre\ni\nThe ever alert management of the\nLyric Theatre added further to their\nmany recent improvements for added\ncomfort and pleasantness of at\nmosphere by redecorating the walls\n\u2666his week. The new colors are brown\nand tan, and they add a freshness\nand charm to the theatre which is\npleasant to the eye and puts one in\n1he proper mood to enjoy the enter\ntainment set before him.\nOther recent improvements include\na new screen, new equipment for\nbettering the ventilation, and added\nimprovements on the fine sound j\nequipment which is proving so satis-:\nfactory to local movie fans. I\nKENOVA VOTES BONDS\nA special levy to raise approxi- i\nmately $20,000 over the next two I\nyears, to be raised for local partici- I\npation in a municipal improvement j\nprogram, financed principally by fed- j\neral funds, was carried yesterday in\na special election at Kenova by a vote\nof 708 to 344.\n'f\u2019he proposed improvements in\nclude flood protection projects, j\nstreets, low cost housing, and a sur\nvey on city-owned water works.\nsnores' for both, and n vet ran an! or,\nThomas Chalmers, who recently ap\npeared with Tallulah Bankhead in\n\"Anthony and Cleopatra,\u201d narrates\n(he story of \u201cThe River,\" as he did in\n\u201cThe Plow.\"\nOpportune Release\nJust as \"The Plow\u201d appeared at a\ntime when the government was em\nphasizing the need of wide-spread\nsoil conservation and relief for share\ncroppers, so \u201cThe River\u201d is' released\nat a time when the government is on\na new .-piest Pending before congress\nis the Norris bill proposing to create\nseven national authorities to build\ndams, abate floods, recreate farming,\nimprove navigation\u2014and generate\npower. The President advocated en\nactment of the legislation by the\nspecial session.\nThe film cost $55,000 to produce and\nit takes a half hour of show time.\n\u201cThe Plow\" cost $20,000 and runs off\nin ahout the same time. The differ\nence in cost lies in the fact that\nwhile \u201cThe Plow\u201d was filmed only in\nfour states caught within the \u201cDust\nBowl,\u201d the new picture was photo\ngraphed over 13 states by three\nparties' of cameramen operating under\nfar more difficult conditions.\n\u201cThe Plow,\u201d in its two years of ex\nistence, has been shown to 10.000,000\npersons in 3.000 commercial theatres\nand is enjoying a revival now in con\nnection with th\" projected appearance\nof \u201cthe river.\u201d \u201cThe River\u201d is already\n\u2014Turn to Page Seven\nThe Law Of Survival Of The Fittest\nWill Make The Semi-Final And\nFinal Matches Of The Kiwanis\nBenefit Tourney Fast And Thrill\ning\u2014Heavyweight Melee Between\nVerlin Adams And Goose Hensley\nLooms As Feature Event\nWith the chaff of the .amateur crop\neliminated from the Kiwdnis benefit\nboxing tournament in the first round\nmatches staged at the Memorial build\ning Monday and Tuesday nights, the\nquarter-final, semi-final and final\nbouts to be held through the remain\nder of this week will be packed with\nthrills and excitdment as the skilled\nsurvivors face each other for the\nchampionships of the different\nclasses.\nThe tournament is under the spon\nsorship of the Kiwanis club, and the\nproceeds are to he used in the club's\nunderprivieged children\u2019s fund. Lock\nDamron, chairman of the Kiwanis\ncommittee, and Billy Adams, veteran\nfight promoter have i ined their\ntalents to produce a mos successful\ntournament as the earh bouts have\nshown: and they arc m king every\npreparation to take care of the fight\nfans and other charitable citizens of\nMingo and Pike counties who will\nturn out to sec the host fights' which\nare to ccme tonight and Friday night\nbeginning promptly at S 15.\nOf outstanding interest is the\nBow for Maxie\n_(\nMax Baer\u2014waiting\nYou\u2019d think Max Baer,\nheavyweight boxing ck\n'\"as waiting to meet Joe\nring whan this\ntaken. But no. Max was\nliis wife's visit from the\nlie showed all the chant\nof an expectant father\nland hospital. It was a\neight pounder and pot-'\ning champion.\nformer\nnpion,\nuis in\nI was\nalting\nk and\nrlstica\nOak\ny. an\nbox\nJealousy Assigned As Motive\nFor Slaying ol Matewan Woman\nheavyweight championship match\nwhich will bring together Verlin\nAdams', the powerful captain-fullback\nof the 1937 Wolfpack, and Goose j\nHensley, a hard-slugging heavy- j\nweight. This bout happens to be one\nof those grudge fights' which are so\ntempting to the fight audience\u2019s\npalate, and the verdict will more than\nlikely be pronounced through the\nknockout route.\n\nFreemasons Give\nDinner and Dance\nNearing the end of another success\nful year in its long and creditable\nhistory, O\u2019Brien lodge No. 101 of\nFreemasons gave its traditional an\nnual banquet at the Masonic temple\nTuesday night with Harry M.\nSchwachter, Williamson merchant,\nand Wilson Chafin, master of the\nlodge at Matewan, the principal\nspeakers on the after-dinner pro\ngram. They appeared in the place of\nGov. Homer A. Holt and Grand\nMaster Herschel H. Rose who were\nprevented by the condition of the\nroads from attending.\nThe dinner was attended by more\nthan 300 members of the order and\nmembers of their families, and was\nfollowed by the annul dance begin\nning at 10 o\u2019clock.\nThe menu was prepared and served\nbv committees of Elizabeth chapter.\nOrder of the Eastern Star, with\nturkey and all the best chosen ac\ncessories constituting the meal. When\n(hey were introduced to the diners,\nMrs'. Maragret Blevins, worthy ma\ntron of the chapter, and members of\nher committees drew a round of\nhearty applause as the authors of one\nof the best banquets ever spread in\ncity.\nThe invocation was given by the\nRev. J. C. Jones, pastor of the First\nBaptist church. J, E. Wilkinson,\nchairman of the committee on ar\nrangements, acted as toastmaster and\nopened the after-dinner session by\nintroducing Sol N. Steffan. worship\nful master of\u2014O\u2019Brien- lodge. Mr.\nSteffan reviewed briefly some of the\nactivities of the lodge the past year,\nand introduced the other officers and\nformer masters present, to whom he\ngraciously paid tribute for their serv\nices to the order. With the enthusiasm\nof his dynamic nature Mr. Steffan\nwarmly welcomed the lodge's guests,\nstarting the program with a zest and\nspirit in maintained to the end.\nNo small feature of the evening's\nentertainment was the musical pro\ngram. on which Mi-s Ruth McCoy,\nMr<. Gladys Lind and Miss Margaret\nAnn Young appeared in solo numbers\nand encores. They wore accompanied\nby Mrs. C. A. Engle talented leader\nin the city's music circles\nDistinguished visitors taking a bow\non their introduction by Toastmaster i\nWilkinson included Mayor J. T ntt\nSmith. Sheriff William E. Burchett,\nAubrey F. Goff, high priest of the\nRoyal Arch chapter; Byron W. i\nThornton, of Hermit lodge; A. H. Me-j\nCoy and J. P. Grace of Freeborn\nlodge., and James Echols of the\nMasonic lodge at Stone.\nTelegrams of regret at their in\nability to attend the dinner were read\nfrom Governor Holt,. Grand Master j\nRose. Judge Charles W. Ferguson,!\nJohn S. Hall, clerk of the house of'\nLewis and Green At Odds\nPowerful labor leaders to re.irh asrreeTv.ent in filed th.it divide? trade\nunionism in*.-* \u2019wo He eiitnps. both seeking the lion\u2019s share.\n*--TVKxrKJZ Tt ufrra.1\nTl't1 hrea oh \\vl; no n i oh 1 \"1 n\n1 hor into (wo host;v Vt>p> touching\nov cry city and hamiet\nmm:' it's 11 nhlV!1 I \\v;\u201d\n1 f of Vro-.-n, rs John\nLewis an.I William CPe,- dis\ncover a formula I'oivvrv diems, U.\nwhich would bo ruiUuoi\u2019v coop'ablo\nlii tboir fall win;;', v. rites 1 iff\ncorrespondent for the Christian\nScience Monitor from Washington\nturday Ho sa vs\nEfforts of moderates on 1 e.*Ji -ides\nof the fence to reunite the labor n ove\ni meat will yo on. The situation is r.o\nworse today than it was last week\ni h< fore the effort nt perso. al med'\nat ion between the p\u00bbino!pn!\u00ab \",f!- nt\ni tempted The work of exploration\nfor some common ground will con\ntinue. Hut it is incontestable today\nthat the effort to find a solution\nthrough a direct meeting of the prin\ncipals has failed.\nThe two. assisted bv Thill ip Mur\nray for the C. r O and George\nHenderson for the American feder\nation of TatV'or. met three t :mes in\ntwo days Their final meeting last\nnight ended with admission bv all\nparticipants that nothing had been,\naccomplished to n 111\"* the situation.\nMr Green expressed it as being a\ncontinuation of \u2019he \"status quo.\nA mooting of the executive coun\ncil of the American Federation\nof F iber during the d iv is helieved\nto have pav. d the way for the im\npasse between Mr. Ia'wus and Mr.\nMrs. Mora Chafin Shot to Death in Mate wan\nStreet by Mrs. Zell Collins After a Question\nof a Personal Nature Was Asked the Victim\nof Gunfire\u2014Both Women Wives and Mothers\nand Widely Known Residents of Mate wan\u2014\nPolice Witnesses Tragedy.\ndelegates, and E. A. Hansbargf r. of\nCharleston, and Past Grand Master\nLawson D. Willis of Kenova.. Wells\nGondykoontz, a past master of\nO'Brien lodge, wrote that his absence\nfrom the city prevented his attend\nance for the first time in the history\nof the lodge\u2019s anniverstay dinnei\u20193.\nThe absence of Mr. Willis was re\nmarked by many of the older mem\nbers of the order. As an official of\n\u2022he grand lodge he presided at the lay\ning of the corner stone of the temple\nand at its dedication to Masonic uses.\nHe has been a regular attendant at the\nannual celebrations, and expressed\nregret that he could not he present\nTuesday night.\nOther members of the general com\nmittee in charge of the function were\nHarry Lovith. W. Earl White. Tedd\nHaynes. Robert Carr, Charles Albert\nand Sid L. Varney\nThe affair was voted generally the\nmost en.ioyable function staged by\nO'Brien lodge in many years.\nLon\" Illness Fatal\nTo Mrs. A. W. Damron\nMrs. A. W. Damron. 49 years old\nand a rosidnt of Huntington for the\npast ?ft .years died in a Huntington\nhosnital earlv Saturday morning. De-I\ncember 4. after a long illness.\nMrs. Damron was the daughter of j\nMrs. Martha Chafin and the late John i\nChafin of Delbarton. She was active\nin the congregation of the First Pres- j\nbyterian church -of Huntington where\nfuneral services were held Sunday\nafternoon.\nActive pallbearers were Will Whit\nted and Fred Wells, both of Logan;\nThomas Powell, J. H. Leith. F\u2019ed\nNicholson and Elmer Bartce of\nHuntington.\nHonorary pallbearers nnmd were\nDr. H D. Hatfield. Dr. E. E Coffey,\nDr. T. I. Hirsehmnn, Dr. Don Kes\nsler. Dr. R. M. Wvlie, Dr. J. E. Hub\nhard, Dr. A. K Kessler. E. L. Hog\nsett. John F. Hamilton, all of Hunt\nington: Dr. H. H. Farley and Rev. J.\nG. McNeeley. both of Logan: Rev.\nHenry Mullens, of Wayne- Joe Orie\ngor. J. Mat Smith. P. B. Maynard. M.\n7 White. Guy White. Rev. Hi May\nnard. Hyman Bank. Eli Sohn Green\nway Hatfield and Willis Parsons, all\nof Williamson: E. P. Curr. P.erwin.\nand McGinnis Hatfield, of Weir a.\nSurviving are her husband, two\ndaughters Miss Clara Damron.\nMiami. Fla., and Mrs. Hugh Ram\nsey, Charleston W. Va.: two sisters.\nMrs. Fulton Mitchell, Logan, and\nMrs. Boyd Adkins Delbarton, W. Ya.:\nher brother. Greenway Chafin, Del\nbarton. and hoi grand-daughter. Sally\nHugh Ramsey, Charleston.\nREVENUE COLLECTOR NAMED\nCollector of Internal Revenue F\nR. Yoke has named Robb Keyser of\nBelington .as assistant collector.\nThe c< -:il a-; m\nextern--'! v t an-? hip\nn t t fir ini' mi itior. n M\nr ''ii laid before tb.n fedora t ion's\nrxecut ivp cnuni Ta\u25a0 C T O de\nn\u2019ar.ds which he hiil obtained from\nMr. Lewis the pros imn day, and that\nthr council either rejected them flaf\nlv or made counter proposes which\nMr. Lewie! in turn re tooted last night.\nGreat Obstacle\nTt is know that the one gtent ob\nstaele to reconciliation i-: the number\nof industries which would !>o opened\nto the industrial form of unionization\ni the T O. form 1 in the event of a\nrun: at. Mr, Lewis is believed to he\nasking- for SO and expecting to get a\nminimum of la. The executive coun\ncil of tiie federati m is believed to\nhave been willing to e ueede five.\nBut tiie gap between five ar.d la is\na wide one -too wide for any bridge\nwhich the peace makers have yet\nbeen able to design.\nWit it happened last night at the\nfour-man meeting of leaders will he\nreported hack to the official nego\ntiation committees of the two or\nganizations on Dec. ST That this\nmeeting is set for a day so far off\nis in itself an indication of how little1\nthere is to report IT id the principals\nmade any progress the results would\nhaw been reported hick to the full\nTli< f,.ct that any report :,t all is\n\u2014Turn To Page Two\nCharged with shooting to death\nMrs. Mora Chafin, 26 years old and\nthe mother of four children, in a pub\nlie steet in Matewan Saturday night,\nMrs. Zell Collins, young and refined\nwife of William Collins and the moth\ner of two children, is a felony prison\n6r m the Min\u00ae\u00b0 county pail in th\u00ab\ntechnical custody of the man whose\nB1Ster was fhe victim of the sensa\ntional shooting. Mrs. Chafin was a\ns ster of County Jailer Henry Reid.\nThe tragedy that sent young Mrs.\nChafin to her grave and will send\nyoung Mrs. Collins to the prisoner's\nbox in circuit court next month on 8\nmurder charge took place at fl:40\nSaturday evening. According to eye\nwitnesst s. Mrs. Chafin was a visitor\nin a confectionery operated bv Mrs.\nia Chambers when Mrs. Collins en\nMrs\" Chfi Pl',C'\u2019 n,Kl denianded tha*\nMis Chnfm come out into the street.\nOn reaching \u2018he sidewalk, and after\nshe had asked Mrs. Chafin some\nonestions of a personal nature. Mrs.\nollms opened fire with a .12 calibre\nPistol. One bullet struck Mrs. Chafin\nm the right hand and three others\nentered her body.\nThe wounded woman was rushed\nn e Matewan Clinic where she died\nSunday evening, about 24 hours after\nthe tragedy took place. Hallie Cham\nbers, Matewan police chief, witnessed\nthe shooting taking Mrs. Collins Into\ncustody with the smoking weapon still\nn her hands. She was turned over\nto the custody of the county jailer\nSaturday night, where she will prob\nably remain a. prisoner until her trial\nin circuit court. She has waived a\npreliminary hearing before Justice of\nj the Peace Robert E. Clifton.\nI Considerable mystery surrounds the\ncircur\"staiv\u2019\"s landing mi t() the\ntiagedv. Jealously is advanced by\nMatewan townspeople. although\nfriends of the slam woman bitterly\ndeny there wo-- nnv foundation for\nsuch feeling he ween the two women.\nI,0'h w nave h.: widely and\nfavorably i..n Matewan and\nvicinity, Hrs Collin-* is a\nof i ho Matewan hi eh school and hag\noff ended college. She is a native of\ni ho f<>\\vn and is known a-s a quiet and\nrefined woman devoted to her hus\nband and two children, the younger\nchild he in ir hut five weeks old. Her\nhusband is a mine worker employed\nnv the Re1 Jacket Coal corporation\nr*t Keen Mountain, Virginia.\nMi\u2019s. Chafin was a member of g-ood\nfamily, her mother. Mrs. C H Reid,\nresiding at Delbarton where a brother\nand three sisters also live. She was\nthe former wife of Walter Rusk from\n1 whom she was divorced some months\nagr>. She was the mother of four\nchildren, three of whom live with\ntheir father. The oldest child, a son.\nhas lived with his mother and her\nhusband at Matewan since their mar\ni riage following the mother's divorce\nfrom Mr Rusk. The lad is a Cudent\nI in the Matewan schools. Mr Chafin\nis a mine worker, also employed by\nthe Red Jacket Cod corporation.\nUnofficial investigation of the fatal\naffair has rew d.'d no ')Ther prof-able\nmof ive for the shooting b n jealous\nlv. and the belief has been op- ae,]\nbv neighbors of Mm Mrs\nCollins. ha\\ ing ro-oMv\nnr-.o-,.; i, Tr,:0-V-r rnv-' h.\nf;l!!v 1, ra n a d. while\nCopies to no-- a\nRaw officials doo'o o -o p.-o\na ffa i r. md it is unders\u2019o -nV \\fr.:\nCollins lias made no s*a* cmeru of \u2022h.-%\nreasons or motive for hor sensational\nact.\nFuneral services\u2019 for Mrs Chafin\nwere held Tuesdav afternoon a* Re\nMethodist church at Mute wan. The\nlv<\u2019v. A. R, Tulloh officiated. \"Burial\n\\cns mad*' in the Fairview cem*'t\u201c!\u2019v in\nWest Williamson. Mrs. Chafin is\nsurvived by her husband. M ra Cha\nfin; two brothers. Jailer Henry R 'id\nand Richard Reid; three sisters. MR*\nKthel Reid. Mis. Mary Hatfield and\nMrs. Pat tv Maynard; and bv her\nmother. Mrs. C. H. Reid, of D hr\nton\nJ. W. Yost\u2019s Brother\nDies At Vets Hospital\nC. A Yost of Olen Aium, a bro'hor\n>'f Road S\u2019lperintondont ,T \\V Yost.\nPifth appro to. dtod in tho Vrtorars\nbospiral at Huntinjrton aft or an rx\ntondrd illnoss Punorat sorvt\"-\\s uv-rp\nhold at Pliirfiold Wolnoolay.\nIn addition to ,T W Vk\u2018 (.r aw.!\nis surivod by o fh.\u25a0 r and\nthr.-,> sish'rs: It P Y Poannkw\nMrs J n ntv.wn SibriVa, y-v\nMrs W A F..vn\\,in T o:--v:l!o: Mr,.\nR J Vaughan Texarkana. Toxas.","height":"30568","width":"22888"}}
